Q1. What is a String in Java?
    In Java, a String is like a container that holds words, sentences, or even entire paragraphs.
    It's simply a way to store text so that the computer can easily use and manage it.

Standard Definition:
    A String in Java is a sequence of characters used to represent text.
    It is treated as a single data type and is enclosed in double quotes (" ").

Q2. How Strings Work in Java: More Than Just Text 🔧
    Java doesn’t store text as simple characters. Strings in Java are special objects,
    meaning they come with extra features and abilities.

    Let’s say you create a String:
        String mypassion = "I love Java programming!";

    The text “I love Java programming!” is now stored in the mypassion box.
    Whenever you reference mypassion, Java knows it contains “I love Java programming!”

# Strings Are Immutable (They Can’t Change) 🔒
    Once you put something inside a String box in Java, you cannot change what’s inside. If you want to change it,
    Java will create a new box with the updated content, leaving the original untouched.

    Let’s take a look at this example:
        String kodnest = "Hello";
        kodnest = kodnest + " World!";

    • Initially, the kodnest box contains “Hello”.
    • When you add ” World!”, Java creates a new box that holds “Hello World!”, while the original “Hello” remains the same.

This is why we say Strings are immutable—once created, they cannot be changed.
If you modify a string, Java simply makes a new string with the updated content.

# Memory Saver: String Pool in Java:
    Java uses a smart method to save memory called the String Pool. The String Pool is like a shared storage area inside the Heap
    where Java keeps commonly used strings. When you create a string, Java checks if the string already exists in the pool.
        • If the string is already there, Java reuses it.
        • If it’s a new string, Java adds it to the pool.

    Here’s an example:
        String kodnest1 = "Java";
        String kodnest2 = "Java";  // Reuses the same "Java" string from the pool
    In this case, both kodnest1 and kodnest2 refer to the same “Java” string in memory,
    which saves space and makes your program more efficient.

# Two Ways to Create Strings in Java ✌️
    Java gives you two ways to create strings:

    1. Using Double Quotes (Recommended):
        This is the most common and easiest way to create a string:
            String kodnest = "Hello Kodnest!"; // it will create inside the string pool

    2. Using the new Keyword (Less Common):
        You can also create a string using the new keyword:
            String kodnest = new String("Hello Kodnest!"); it will create inside the heap section but outside the String pool

    While both methods work, using double quotes is generally more efficient because it reuses strings from the String Pool.

